      <hedline>
        <hl1>Praise, Without Rules</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Julie E Maybee letter on guidelines for raising children (Oct 18 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''New Advice for Parents: Saying 'That's Great!' May Not Be'' (news article, Oct. 18):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''New Advice for Parents: Saying 'That's Great!' May Not Be'' (news article, Oct. 18):</p>
        <p>Instead of following rules that say we should not praise our children so much or following rules that say we should praise our children more, perhaps we should just stop following rules altogether.</p>
        <p>The best praise takes into account the child's needs and personality, as well as the current situation that the child is in. What a particular child needs in terms of praise in one situation may be different from what that same child needs in another situation, and different from what a different child needs in that same situation.</p>
        <p>We would do better to listen to our children when we praise, rather than to rules.</p>
        <p>JULIE E. MAYBEE  Yonkers, Oct. 22, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
